 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 118) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Two historical events are especially significant to the study of management. First, in 1776, Adam Smith published \i The Wealth of Nations\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 , in which he argued the economic advantages that organizations and society would gain from the \b division of labor\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  (or job specialization). The division of labor involved the breakdown of jobs into narrow and repetitive tasks. Smith's work showed that division of labor increased productivity by increasing each worker's skill and dexterity. It also saved time lost in changing tasks, and it encouraged the development of labor\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 saving inventions and machinery. Division of labor continues to be popular as a principle for managing work.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 The second important event is the \b Industrial Revolution\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 , which started in the late eighteenth century. During the Industrial Revolution, machine power was substituted for human power. This made it more economical to manufacture goods in factories rather than at home. The shift to factory work increased the need for management professionals. Large efficient factories needed managers to forecast demand and to ensure that enough material was on hand to make products. Managers were also needed to assign tasks to people and to direct daily activities. The increase in managers in turn necessitated the development of formal theories to guide managers in running large organizations.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 119) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 Frederick Taylor did most of his work at the Midvale and Bethlehem Steel Companies in Pennsylvania. As a mechanical engineer with a Quaker and Puritan background, he was continually appalled by workers' inefficiencies. Employees used vastly different techniques to do the same job. They were inclined to "take it easy" on the job, and Taylor believed that worker output was only about one\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 third of what was possible. Virtually no work standards existed. Workers were placed in jobs with little or no concern for matching their abilities and aptitudes with the tasks they were required to do. Managers and workers were in continual conflict. Taylor set out to correct the situation by applying the scientific method to shop floor jobs. He spent more than two decades passionately pursuing the "one best way" for each job to be done.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \ul\f185\tx360 Taylor's Four Principles of Management\f353\par \pard \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tx360\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 a.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Develop a science for each element of an individual's work, which will replace the old rule\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 of\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 thumb method.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 b.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Scientifically select and then train, teach, and develop the worker.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 c.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Heartily cooperate with the workers so as to ensure that all work is done in accordance with the principles of the science that has been developed.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx360 d.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Divide work and responsibility almost equally between management and workers. Management takes over all work for which it is better fitted than the workers.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 120) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Frank Gilbreth is probably best known for his experiments in bricklaying. By carefully analyzing the bricklayer's job, he reduced the number of motions in laying exterior brick from 18 to about 5, and on laying interior brick the motions were reduced from 18 to 2. Using the Gilbreth's techniques, the bricklayer could be more productive on the job and less fatigued at the end of the day. The Gilbreths were among the first researchers to use motion pictures to study hand\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 and\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 body motions and the amount of time spent doing each motion. Wasted motions missed by the naked eye could be identified and eliminated. The Gilbreths also devised a classification scheme to label 17 basic hand motions, which they called therbligs. This scheme allowed the Gilbreths a more precise way of analyzing a worker's exact hand movements.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 121) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 Fayol described the practice of management as something distinct from accounting, finance, production, distribution, and other typical business functions. He argued that management was an activity common to all human endeavors in business, in government, and even in the home. He then proceeded to state 14 principles of management\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 fundamental rules of management that could be taught in schools and applied in all organizational situations.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \ul\f185\tx380 Fayol's 14 Principles of Management\f353\par \pard \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tx380\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 1.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Division of work\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 specialization increases output by making employees more efficient.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 2.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Authority\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 managers must be able to give orders and authority, gives them this right. \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 3.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Discipline\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 employees must obey and respect the rules that govern the organization.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 4.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Unity of command\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 every employee should receive orders from only one superior.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 5.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Unity of direction\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the organization should have a single plan of action to guide managers and workers.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 6.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Subordination of individual interests to the general interest\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the interests of any one employee or group of employees should not take precedence over the interests of the organization as a whole.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 7.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Remuneration\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 workers must be paid a fair wage for their services.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 8.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Centralization\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 this term refers to the degree to which subordinates are involved in decision making.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 9.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Scalar chain\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 the line of authority from top management to the lowest ranks is the scala\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 chain.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 10.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Order\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 people and materials should be in the right place at the right time.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 11.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Equity\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 managers should be kind and fair to their subordinates.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 12.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Stability of tenure of personnel\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 management should provide orderly personnel planning and ensure that replacements are available to fill vacancies.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 13.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Initiative\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 employees who are allowed to originate and carry out plans will exert high levels of effort.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\tx380 14.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\tab \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Esprit de corps\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 \u57348 _\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 promoting team spirit will build harmony and unity within the organization.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 122) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 In Max Weber's model, an ideal bureaucracy contains six elements. The first of these is a \b division of labor\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 , through which jobs are broken down into simple, routine, and well\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 defined tasks. The second element is an \b authority hierarchy\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 , in which job positions are organized within a clear chain of command. The third element is \b formal selection\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 , through which personnel are selected for jobs based on their technical qualifications.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 The fourth element of Weber's model is \b formal rules and regulations\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . Weber believed that a bureaucracy should be organized according to a system of written rules and standard operating procedures. Fifth, Weber believed that bureaucracies should be characterized by \b impersonality\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . Through this element, rules and controls could be applied in a uniform way, not according to individual personalities. Finally, Weber's bureaucratic model includes a sixth element\: \b career orientation\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . Weber saw managers not as owners of the units they manage, but instead as career professionals.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 123) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Without question, the most important contribution to the developing organizational behavior field came from the Hawthorne Studies, a series of studies conducted at the Western Electric Company Works in Cicero, Illinois. Western Electric industrial engineers initially designed these studies as a scientific management experiment. They wanted to examine the effect of various illumination levels on worker productivity. Based on their research, it was concluded that illumination intensity was not directly related to group productivity. \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 In 1927, the Western Electric engineers asked Harvard professor Elton Mayo and his associates to join the study as consultants. Through additional research, Elton Mayo concluded that group influences affected individual behavior, that group standards establish individual worker output, and that money is less a factor in determining output than are group standards, group sentiments, and security. These conclusions led to a new emphasis on the human behavior factor in the functioning of organizations and the attainment of their goals.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 124) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 The systems approach contributes to our understanding of management first by helping us to understand that organizations are made up of interdependent factors. As managers coordinate work activities in the various units of the organization, they must ensure that all of the interdependent units are working together so that the organization's goals can be achieved. The systems approach recognizes that an organization's overall performance is dependent upon the efforts of many units working together.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Second, the systems approach helps us to understand that decisions and actions taken in one organizational area will affect others and vice versa. For example, if the purchasing department of a company doesn't acquire the right quantity and quality of inputs, that company's production department will not be able to do its job effectively.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Third, the systems approach recognizes that organizations are not self\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 contained. They rely on their environments for essential inputs. They also use their environments as outlets to absorb their outputs. No organization can survive for long if it ignores government regulations, supplier relations, or the varied external constituencies upon which it depends.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 125) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 One important contingency variable is the \b size \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 of an organization. As the size of an organization increases, so do the problems of coordination. For instance, the type of organization structure appropriate for an organization of 50,000 employees is likely to be inefficient for an organization of 50 employees. A very large organization might require a more hierarchical management structure. A small organization, on the other hand, might thrive with less hierarchy in its management structure.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 A second popular contingency variable concerns the \b routineness of task technology\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . To achieve its purpose, an organization must use technology. Routine technologies require organizational structures, leadership styles, and control systems that differ from those required by customized or nonroutine technologies. An auto manufacturing plant, for instance, might use routine technologies such as robots to perform automated work. These robots would require a much different type of management than would be required within a service business, such as a fast food restaurant, where employees' customer service performance must be supervised.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 A third contingency variable is \b environmental uncertainty\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . The degree of uncertainty caused by environmental changes influences the management process. What works best in a stable and predictable environment may be totally inappropriate in a rapidly changing and unpredictable environment. A company that is going through a merger, for instance, might require its managers to focus on helping employees cope with management transitions. A company that is in a more stable environment might encourage its managers to focus on employee productivity and company growth.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 A fourth contingency variable concerns \b individual differences\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 . Individuals differ in terms of their desire for growth, autonomy, tolerance of ambiguity, and expectations. These and other individual differences are particularly important when managers select motivation techniques, leadership styles, and job designs. An individual who desires a great deal of autonomy on the job might need to be managed in a very "hands off" style, for example. An individual who is very motivated by team success might need to have his or her work activities structured to involve a great deal of group interaction.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 126) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 1\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Work is an act of worship\:  In Islam, worship is not confined to ritual practices such as prayers and fasting, but has a broader understanding.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 2\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Responsibility of employees \plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  work as trust (Amana)\:  Amana means being faithful to the employer and the organization.  \plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 3\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Reliance on own self\: Islam encourages work and hence the importance of depending on one's self in work.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 4\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Responsibility of employers \plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  proper placement\:  Assigning each person job tasks that match his or her skills and talents is very important.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 5\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Responsibility of employers \plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  fairness and humane treatment of employees\: Employees are respected and have the right to receive fair and timely wages.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 6\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Quality (Itqan)\:  One should not only do a 'good enough' job; He or she should try their best to produce a high quality product and deliver a high quality service.\plain\f353\fs20\cf0\par \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0 7\plain\f353\fs20\cf0 -\plain\f185\fs20\cf0  Consultative decision making (Shura)\:  This is a major pillar in Islamic political thinking, but it also has implications on on business organizations.
 \par\sect\sectd\sbknone \cols2\colno1\colw480\colsr60\colno2\colw10260 \pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\qr 127) \line \sect\sbkcol\pard \plain\f185\fs20\cf0\plain\f185\fs20\cf0 Because of the differences in theory and practice from one Arab context to the next, it has been difficult to come up with one single theory of Arab management. While some would rightfully acknowledge the role of Islam in shaping Arab managerial perspectives and behavior, the presence of many other religions, races, and cultural traditions, means that Islamic managerial perspectives cannot be presented as representing the only Arab theory of management. For example, Christians have significant presence in countries such as Lebanon and Egypt. In addition to religion, there has been a significant role for tribal culture, colonial bureaucracies, western influence, government interventions, and political constraints. These factors play differently in different Arab contexts and, accordingly, Arab managerial thinking and behavior tend to differ, sometimes significantly and sometimes marginally, from one country to another.
